*{{Cite certification|type=single|title=Can't Fight the Moonlight|artist=LeAnn Rimes|region=United States|award=Platinum|certyear=2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Official Singles Chart on 19/11/2000 |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20001119/7501/ |access-date=2024-08-02 |website=Official Charts |language=en}}</ref> In Australia, the song was the biggest-selling single of 2001, where it peaked at number 1 for six weeks, topped the year-end chart, and was certified triple Platinum.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARIA Top 100 Year End Singles Chart 2001 |url=http://cdn.aria.com.au/pdfs/A21605E01B470ED02036A89919C08BCB45CFBA22FCD5D4DAFD27D0F3636CD5BD/ARIA%20Top%20100%20Singles%20Chart%20-%202001.pdf?seq=42 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240802194839/http://cdn.aria.com.au/pdfs/A21605E01B470ED02036A89919C08BCB45CFBA22FCD5D4DAFD27D0F3636CD5BD/ARIA%20Top%20100%20Singles%20Chart%20-%202001.pdf?seq=42 |archive-date=August 2, 2024 |access-date=2024-08-02 |website=www.aria.com.au |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=jmcmullen |date=2017-03-01 |title=The 20 Best Songs You Didn't Know Were Disney Songs |url=https://d23.com/the-20-best-songs-you-didnt-know-were-disney-songs/ |access-date=2024-08-02 |website=D23 |language=en-US}}</ref> In total, the song received Platinum certifications from six countries and Gold certifications from a further three.<ref name=CFTMcerts/> "Can't Fight the Moonlight" won Rimes a ''[[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]]'' for "Favorite Song from a Movie".<ref name="rock" />

[[File:LeAnn Rimes.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Rimes performing in September 2004]]
In November 2000, Rimes sued Curb to nullify her recording contract with the label; it had originally been signed on her behalf by her parents five years earlier.<ref name="mtv">{{cite web |last = Flippo |first = Chet |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1274452/leann-rimes-sues-label.jhtml |title = LeAnn Rimes Sues Label In Attempt To End Contract – Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher = MTV |date = November 17, 2000 |access-date = October 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110428105356/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1274452/leann-rimes-sues-label.jhtml |archive-date = April 28, 2011 }}</ref> In January 2001, Curb released the compilation ''[[I Need You (album)|I Need You]]'', which consists of four previously released soundtrack appearances alongside six new tracks.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rimes |first1=LeAnn |title=''I Need You'' (CD Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[Curb Records]] |date=January 30, 2001 |id=8573876382}}</ref> Rimes publicly disowned the album; she said that it was compiled from studio outtakes and released without her knowledge or input.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1474877/leann-rimes-disowns-new-album.jhtml |title = News : LeAnn Rimes Disowns New Album |publisher = CMT |date = February 3, 2001 |access-date = September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120320054634/http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1474877/leann-rimes-disowns-new-album.jhtml |archive-date = March 20, 2012 }}</ref> Despite her comments, Curb continued to promote the record and released three singles in support of the album. The first of these releases was "[[But I Do Love You]]", which had previously appeared on the ''Coyote Ugly'' soundtrack and was remixed in a country style for inclusion on ''I Need You''.<ref name=ccorner>{{cite magazine |magazine =Billboard |last1=Jessen |first1=Wade |title=Country Corner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA33 |date=February 17, 2001 |page=33}}</ref> This version peaked at number 20 on the country songs chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> ''I Need You'' generally featured more pop-oriented songs than her previous releases, being described by Stephen Erlewine as "her first full-fledged pop album" with "footing squarely within adult contemporary pop".<ref name="erlewineINY">{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/i-need-you-bonus-tracks-mr0000344134 |title=I Need You [Bonus Tracks&#93; - LeAnn Rimes |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] |date=January 30, 2001 |access-date=September 28, 2011}}</ref> Chris Neal from ''[[Country Weekly]]'' praised the album and Rimes's vocal performance, saying that "all the songs are solid". However, he also noted that "most of the songs have only a tenuous connection to country" and said "how you feel about ''I Need You'' will largely depend on whether you see LeAnn’s shift toward pop as a positive development."<ref name="CWeeklyINY">{{Cite web |last=Neal |first=Chris |date=February 26, 2001 |title=Music Reviews: I Need You (Curb Records) |url=http://www.countryweekly.com/stories/reviews.cfm?instanceid=9865 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020612191056/http://www.countryweekly.com/stories/reviews.cfm?instanceid=9865 |archive-date=June 12, 2002 |website=Country Weekly}}</ref> In November 2001, Rimes was released from her original contract with Curb and subsequently signed a new agreement with the label under new terms.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Staff |first=Billboard |date=2001-11-30 |title=Rimes Ends Dispute, Re-Signs With Curb |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/rimes-ends-dispute-re-signs-with-curb-77578/ |access-date=2024-07-25 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> ''I Need You'' was reissued with additional tracks on March 23, 2002.<ref name="bn">{{cite web|url=http://music.barnesandnoble.com/I-Need-You/LeAnn-Rimes/e/715187873827 |title=I Need You [Bonus Tracks&#93;, LeAnn Rimes, Music CD - Barnes & Noble |publisher=[[Barnes & Noble]] |date=March 26, 2002 |access-date=September 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202052400/http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/i-need-you-leann-rimes/7572407?ean=0715187873827|archive-date=February 2, 2016}}</ref> The album was certified Platinum by the RIAA.<ref name="riaa" /> 

On October 1, 2002, Rimes released her seventh studio album ''[[Twisted Angel]]''. The album was mainly produced by [[Desmond Child]] and was a drastic departure from her previous studio albums, containing a combination of dance-pop and adult contemporary with more adult material.<ref name="allmusicbio"/><ref name="erlewineTA">{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=twisted-angel-r606362|tab=review|pure_url=yes}} |title=Twisted Angel - LeAnn Rimes |website=[[Allmusic]] |date=2002-10-01 |access-date=2011-11-09}}</ref> The album was preceded by the single "[[Life Goes On (LeAnn Rimes song)|Life Goes On]]", which experienced success internationally but failed to chart on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brown |first=Jonathan |date=2014-08-19 |title=The 'Twisted' Pop Failure of LeAnn Rimes |url=https://guardianlv.com/2014/08/the-twisted-pop-failure-of-leann-rimes-video/ |access-date=2024-08-02 |website=Guardian Liberty Voice |language=en-US}}</ref> The single was particularly successful in Australia, where it peaked at number seven and was certified Platinum.<ref>{{Cite web |title=australian-charts.com - LeAnn Rimes - Life Goes On |url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=LeAnn+Rimes&titel=Life+Goes+On&cat=s |access-date=2024-08-02 |website=australian-charts.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite certification|region=Australia|type=single|award=Platinum|certyear=2002}}</ref> The second single released from the album was "[[Tic Toc (LeAnn Rimes song)|Tic Toc]]", which became her first top-10 hit on the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref name=":0" /> Rimes received criticism from critics and fans alike for her decision to release a pop album. She explained: "I've gotten grilled a lot about that album. You know, people just didn't want me to experiment. When you're a teenager growing up, you learn alot about yourself, and that's what I did with my music. I did something different, something that not a lot of people expected me to do. [...] And, in a lot of ways, that did work for me. It was a great learning experience. So, nope, no regrets whatsoever."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mayhew |first=Malcolm |date=January 30, 2005 |title=LeAnn Rimes counts on fans to embrace return to country |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G7syAAAAIBAJ&pg=PA31&article_id=6872,6351270|access-date=June 13, 2024 |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |pages=F3–F4 |publication-place=[[Spokane, Washington|Spokane, WA]]}}</ref> ''Twisted Angel'' was certified Gold by the RIAA.<ref name="riaa" /> 

In July 2003, Rimes released her first children's book, titled ''Jag''.<ref name="jag" /> In November, Rimes released her ''[[Greatest Hits (LeAnn Rimes album)|Greatest Hits]]'' compilation in North America; its international counterpart ''[[The Best of LeAnn Rimes]]'' was released in February 2004.<ref name="rock" /> Both compilations included the new recording "[[Last Thing on My Mind (Ronan Keating and LeAnn Rimes song)|Last Thing on My Mind]]", a duet with [[Ronan Keating]] that was released as a single in May 2004. The song was most successful in the United Kingdom, where it peaked at numbers 4 and 5 on the Scottish and UK singles charts, respectively.<ref name=":1" /> In October 2004, Rimes released her first Christmas album and eighth studio album ''[[What a Wonderful World (LeAnn Rimes album)|What a Wonderful World]]''.<ref name="allmusicbio"/>

